Rating: 4
I have made this twice now using country style pork ribs. The meat turns out tender and juicy and the crust is a real taste treat. For those with less tolerance for spicy hot dishes, I recommend reducing the tabasco by half. Use coarse-ground black pepper for the best effect. I also used a smoker rather than a kettle grill. The first time I used hickory chips, the second, apple chips. The apple chips gave it a softer smoke flavor. I'll use this one over and over. Next time, maybe a beef brisket.

Rating: 4
Fantastic recipie, made it for the 4th of July and everyone loved it. Ribs were tender and flavorful. I made 8 1/2 lbs of ribs and they were all gone. I used my Webber gas grill (Off, Off, High) with wood chips in the smoker box and Foil Package full of woodchips with holes poked in the top over the rear burner and kept the temp at 250F for 4 hours and it worked great. FYI: I picked up this tip: to remove the tough skin from the back of the ribs all you have to do is make a small cut under it with a knife about half an inch to get a flap going and then grab it with a paper towel. If you dont us a paper towel you can't pull it off with your fingers but with the towel it comes off easily. I highly recomend that you remove this skin/fat/whatever from the back of you ribs it makes for a better finished product.

Rating: 4
I will never be convinced that a gas grill can perform nearly as well as a coal kettle. You simply cannot get the great, authentic open-flame flavor that defines true barbeque. Use real hardwood coal and soaked chips for better smoking. Also a drip pan filled with chicken stock and spices. Coal or gas, a vertical rib rack allows space for six or more racks at a time. Gas is great for a lot of grilling chores but for this recipe is literally nothing more than an outdoor oven. Of course pro chefs with cooking shows endorse gas. I would too if the company gave me a $10,000 outdoor kitchen free of charge.

