Rating: 3
Your time will be approimately the same. The beauty of the gas grill is that when you learn where 250° is on your dial settings you can always attain that themperature every time and when you set it there it will maintain that temperature throughout the cooking cycle. Also,you don't have to add anything to the fire every 20 minutes. I am a firm believer in the gas grill because of its consistency and dependability. The only secret is to make sure you always have gas on hand. Running out gas halfway through the meal can be embarassing. There are gauges avialable to let you know the level of the gas in each tank you have (invest in one.) Another tip I have and this applies to gas or charcoal grills. Be watchful when using a basting sauce that contains sugar. Sugar will burn even at very low temperatures. My personal preference is cook the ribs with the just the rub until about the last 20 to 30 minutes. Then use the basting sauce for the last 20 to 30 minutes. Don't leave the ribs alone durning that last few minutes as sugar can burn in a minute. Bon Apetit!

